	<transcript sound="sound1"><![CDATA[Food handlers must practice good food hygiene and pest control methods in order to minimise pest-related problems.<br /><br />To reduce the risk of infestation it is important to prevent pests from breeding and to deny them the conditions they like.<br /><br />Let's look at the role of a food handler in controlling pests. <br /><br />In particular, the food handler must:<br /><br /><li>Report signs of pests immediately so the supervisor can contact the pest control operator;</li><li>Report broken or damaged doors, windows, equipment or proofing;</li><li>Report any holes or other entry points to the manager;</li><li>Keep food premises and refuse areas clean and tidy;</li><li>Ensure that any food on display is always covered;</li><li>Always 'clear and clean as you go' and clear away spillages promptly;</li><li>Store food off the floor and clear of the walls to allow regular inspection;</li><li>Check stock regularly and remove or destroy damaged or contaminated stock;</li><li>Ensure that food is stored in pest-proof containers and lids are always replaced;</li><li>Place food or food containers away from electric fly-killers, and ensure the fly-killer is switched on;</li><li>Check that all deliveries of raw materials, packaging and laundry are free from infestation.</li>]]></transcript>

		
	
